segments.text: okay eddie was extension veterinarian now this was about 1945 am i wrong that was uh that was uh in the let me see uh yes uh eddie left here about the first of september of 45 and i went into that office about you know i they they uh they hired i was still in the service
And I thought, well, if I can get a job like that, that'll help me to get out of the service.
But let me see.
In May of 45, Jack Heaton and I had opened our office out here.
We were still in the service.
The old colonel said it was all right with him.
Somebody says, well, if they find out about that in Washington, they'll transfer you clear out of this country.
Well, we said, we've been here too long anyway.
We started that practice, and one of us needed to get out of the service to get out there to it.
So I thought, well, if I can get that job as state veterinarian, I'll be here close to it.
So I took that job that Eddie had, and I was there for a year.
Let me ask you this.
Back in those days, was the state veterinarian really a state veterinarian back then or not?
They had...
They had a lot of authority and a lot of power.
In fact, I used my power in reverse in many instances where I didn't think it was necessary to quarantine a herd or take some kind of action.
Well, I helped
Yeah, for instance, in the fall of 45, there were some Brahma Bulls.
You may know about this.
The Mexicans down there on the border, what were their names?
The Garas?
What?
The Garas.
Garas.
Garas, that's the one.
They brought those...
those red bremas in from Brazil.
Now, when they left Brazil, they were Brazilian bulls.
They got into Mexico, they were Mexican bulls.
They came across the border into Texas.
When they got over here, they reverted back to Brazilian bulls.
Well, we needed that blood.
We needed that blood, you know.
We didn't know about it.
We didn't know about it until the following April.
In April of 46, Francis and I were in Hermosillo, Mexico, at a U.S. and Mexico sanitary meeting.
And somebody told me that we had some Brazilian bulls in Texas.
What are you going to do about it?
I says, I don't know until I get home.
I came home.
Those bulls had been in contact with those highly susceptible cattle from here for six months.
I said, what are you going to do with these bulls?
They said, we're not going to do anything with them.
We're going to keep them right here.
I says, if you'll keep those bulls right here, we're going to have somebody examine them every 30 days, and if anything goes wrong that
if you have any sickness or it looks like you might have some trouble, you contact me and we'll be glad to.
Well, we... What were you looking for?
Well, the first problem that jumped up, the Midwestern states started raising sound about us having those Brazilian bulls down here.
You're talking about the U.S. Livestock Sanitary Commission.
Well, those people were all members of the U.S. Sanitary Commission, U.S. Livestock Sanitary.
But they had a little organization of their own group up there in the Midwest, in Kansas and Nebraska and one or two other states.
And they were going to have a meeting up there about this.
So I got on an airplane and flew up there.
And they were going to quarantine.
They were going to embargo against Texas.
Well, I told them what had happened and how I felt about it and how we were keeping them under observation.
They said, well, that's all right.
That's all right.
We think you've got the thing under control.
So I come on back home.
Wasn't a week later that the Florida people started.
We're going to embargo against Texas cattle.
They've got those Brazilian bulls over there.
I jump on an airplane and fly down to Lake Okeechobee and went into that little old hotel down there and heard a couple of fellas talking and
Yeah, there's a whole delegation of those so-and-sos coming over here, but we're going to quarantine their cattle.
Man, I didn't sleep very good that night.
I thought, well, I'm that delegation.
We got up the next morning and went down to this meeting of the commission.
They were meeting at the courthouse there.
And they were discussing a little fever tick outbreak that they had down there, you know, coming out of the Everglades.
I don't know whether they still got them or not, but every so often those deer and

whatnot will come out of the Everglades and bring those old fever ticks and they have to fight them back you know and they were talking about how they were handling that situation and I said I see they came to me and I got up and I said well I see you this fever tick situation over you people have got problems over here too but I said we're not worried in Texas we we feel like you'll take care of it all right and then I went into details of

what we had done and what we had and how we were handling it and they said well we think that's all right we think you can handle your your problems in Texas too so we broke up here comes an old boy running down there and said shook hands with me and says boy you sure did a good job I said what do you mean he says getting this thing straightened out said you know
If we'd have got that embargo against you, we'd have sure had a good sale of brame of bulls here in Florida.
He was just laughing about it.
So a lot of those things, a lot of those embargoes are just economic things, see, for economic reasons.
But the livestock, I got the general impression that all the, that the Livestock Sanitary Commission didn't necessarily promulgate their rules on the basis of
good veterinary medicine and quarantines and from the basis of good practice in the shipment of cattle, but they were merely there to kind of help keep the rest of the country off the Texas bag.
Is that right?
Oh, I see your point.
That's exactly right.
That's exactly right.
And people...
You know, we had some good feeder cattle down here.
We export a lot more cattle than we use, and we have to constantly be on guard to keep somebody from quarantining against us.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
And a lot of your regulatory laws are simply economic embargo-type things, you know.
The Livestock Sanitary Commission was more in Oregon at that time to keep the livestock industry in good stead with the rest of the country.
Isn't that correct?
More necessarily than to prevent the spread of disease.
Well, I'd go to a U.S. livestock meeting, and I had to be ready to answer questions.
I remember old...
The old doctor, the old veterinarian from Montana, I don't remember his name now, but he got up one day.
No, it was before him.
He got up one day in the meeting, and he says, I would like to know what the states of the anaplasmosis states, namely Texas, Louisiana, Mississippi, and Florida, are doing to control...
Anaplasmosis.
And I thought, good gosh, how am I going to handle that?
I was going to say, that was a pretty tough question.
How am I going to handle that?
Well, this old veterinarian from Arkansas, what was his name?
Well, anyway, he jumped up and says, I don't know what these other states are doing, but
Arkansas ain't doing a damn thing.
If you'll tell us something to do, we'll do it.
Old man just sat down.
Oh, yes.
But you know what?
We're still having to fight that battle.
Why do we have an enormous...
expenditure of money for brucellosis eradication in Texas to appease these other states.
We can handle our business down here.
Now, wait a minute.
Let's cut that machine.
Let me ask you another question now before I run this over you.
Then we can turn it off and get on with what you want to say.
I, for years, carried a tremendous brucellosis titer, which helped me out.
But
We had a lot of people, especially up in Minnesota, that got sick with it.
And there wasn't much you could do for it back in those days.
And there isn't too much more you can do about it now.
Don't you think the public health people are going to keep the heat on?
If you can segregate public health people from veterinary health people, don't you think they're going to really put the heat on to continue to work on that?
They have been for, well, when did we start
playing with that.
54, wasn't it?
Yeah, that was earlier than that, really.
Yeah, yeah, but we had those meetings down in Austin over 30 years ago.
Yes.
And these... these... the USDA will continue to...

put pressure on because they spent two billion dollars and and we haven't got a whole lot to show for it but they're gonna have to continue spending a lot of money on it I guess I don't know I'm not too worried about it I don't think that I don't think that the government ought to pay me to vaccinate calves
But as long as they do it, I'm going to take that money and just lay it and go on.

OK. Dan, I'm sure you weren't out of school very long before you became somewhat involved in what we call organized veterinary medicine associations, the AVMA and TVMA and so forth, and probably belonged to the junior AVMA in school and belonged to the AVMA and the Texas Veterinary Medical Association.
Looking back on it, I'd like to have you give

little bit of a summary of what associations can do for a veterinarian specifically and also what their value is to the general public if you can say the two are different of course well associations are in a position to
do much more than an individual could do in raising the standards of a profession or in changing the rules and regulations or whatnot.
The association does so much that the individual couldn't even attempt to do and when you bring
association matters before a group of individuals that are dedicated and capable and really desiring to come up with the right answers, they can do so much more for the group than an individual can.
And so I know that
that the veterinary profession could never be where it is today without our association.
What do you feel in the Texas Veterinary Medical Association?
Have there been any so-called milestones, or do you feel it's just kind of grown steadily through the years in effectiveness and in its scope?
We've had our ups and downs all down through the years.

the last 40 or 50 years uh but uh when uh when i was a student yes i belonged to the student chapter of avma and then that's one thing that old dr marstella i think uh i can give him a lot of credit for that he he made me feel like that that uh there were there were two things that
were a must.
I must pass the state board, and I must belong to the state association and to the AVMA.
It was just my understanding that that is the thing that you didn't think about doing anything else but belonging and contributing in a small way when the occasion arose.
I just feel that so many people don't stop to think how much better off we are today through organized veterinary medicine.
I'd like to ask you a general question and then a specific question, some specific steps to that.

You know, the Federal Trade Commission has kind of gotten after the professions lately, the dental profession, the medical profession, and the veterinary profession also, regarding their monopolistic trade practices and so forth.
And they've kind of gone a little bit hard on so-called the rules of practice promulgated by the political arms known as the examining boards.
Do you feel there's a happy medium in that?
Do you feel pressures from both sides?
I can see where the participants want to bring it.
